"{\"uid\": \"prevention.com-health-a61635886-olympic-gymnast-aly-raisman-hospitalized-stroke-like-symptoms\", \"text\": \"\\\"It was so scary,\\\" the Olympic gymnast said.  We may earn commission from links on this page, but we only recommend products we back.Why Trust Us?  Since her retirement, Olympic gymnastAly Raismanhas been hospitalized twice for\\\"stroke-like symptoms,\\\"she recently told Alex Cooper on theCall Her Daddypodcast. In the interview, Raisman recounted the experiences and attributed them both to trauma and stress.  \\\"If you do not pick a day to rest, your body will pick it for you,\\\"-that quote, Raisman said,  \\\"encapsulates\\\" her episodes. As a baseline, she tends to have \\\"different minor issues\\\" with her health \\\"depending on what I am going through at the time,\\\" she said, but there were two \\\"intense\\\" events during which she was reviewed for stroke-like symptoms. \\\"I can not remember my name. I am slurring my words. I can barely speak. Both times I was tested for a stroke because I literally could not move my body,\\\" she recalled.  If you are not familiar, the symptoms of astroke, according to theNational Heart, Blood, and Lung Institute, are:  Raisman said it was all \\\"so scary,\\\" a fear that was exacerbated by the PTSD she lives with as a result of the abuse she experienced in medical settings as a young gymnast. In 2018, U.S. gymnastics doctor Larry Nassarwas sentenced to up to 175 years in prisonfor sexually abusing his patients, among other sex crimes. Over 150 women, including Raisman, came forward as victims.  Raisman's past made her understandably wary when it came to being alone with medics during her recent health scares. \\\"The first time it happened was during COVID. And so, they would not let my mom in the ambulance with me,\\\" she recalled. \\\"I was aware enough to know, 'Oh my God, I have two men [with me], I can not move my arms and my legs, I can not move my body, I can not speak. What if they take advantage of me?'\\\"  \\\"I was really still struggling a lot with PTSD,\\\" she added. \\\"People do not realize how much it still lives with you when you have been through something traumatic. So, that was really hard for me.\\\"  The second episode happened a year and a half later, Raisman explained, and struck her with \\\"complete body paralysis\\\" that left her hospitalized for three days. \\\"They would not release me because I could not sit up on my own. It took me so long. I needed help walking, going to the bathroom,\\\" she explained. \\\"It was the most [difficult] to be able to go from being an athlete and being able to push myself so much to literally not even be able to move my fingers, move my legs.\\\"  In the medical community, bouts of stroke-like symptoms are known as \\\"stroke mimics,\\\"  and they have been linked to a series of potential causes including migraines, vertigo, and, commonly, functional neurological disorder (FND), per theAmerican Heart Association (AHA), which is a condition that can affect sensation, movement, speech, and vision. PTSD symptomsare commonin people with FNDs, and researchers think PTSD could even be a cause of them. A recentstudyfound that people who have stroke mimics are susceptible to developing (or developing worsened) PTSD.  \\\"I wonder what is the chicken and what is the egg here?\\\" Natalia Rost, M.D., chief of the stroke division at Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston told the AHA. \\\"Folks who are vulnerable to psychological stress can experience stroke mimics, which could be the strongest connection to developing PTSD after a stroke mimic.\\\"  With so much unknown about stroke mimics, Raisman said she was initially \\\"ignored\\\" by doctors. \\\"It's appalling,\\\" she said. \\\"It wasn't until they realized that I was a very high-level athlete, that they were very nice to me and taking care of me, which is also triggering for me because I already have trust issues with doctors.\\\"  Sinceher retirement from gymnastics in 2020, she has been focusing on her personal life. \\\"I have been doing therapy for many years, and I think therapy can be so impactful and so helpful,\\\" she toldWondermindin 2022. \\\"I am really just trying to remember that it's important for me to just stick with it, be patient, communicate with my therapist, my friends, and family. So I am just kind of taking it day by day.\\\"  During the upcoming Paris Summer Games, Raisman will be an official hospitality ambassador alongside Michael Phelps, perNBC, and she's curious to see how her body will react. \\\"I am gonna be so busy,\\\" she told Cooper. \\\"There is gonna be a lot of triggers. I might see someone that maybe did not protect me in the past. So, it's working on that. It's very complicated.\\\"  16 Skin Spots You Should Get Checked Out Promptly  Dave Coulier Reveals New Cancer Diagnosis  How I Personalized My Severe Asthma Management  FDA: 1.5 Million Bags of Shredded Cheese Recalled  Norovirus Vs. Flu: How to Tell Which You Have  Should You Take Ashwagandha or Magnesium to Sleep?  How I am Handling Life After Bone Marrow Transplant  When Is the Best Time to Take Zinc?  Study: The Best Diets to Prevent Constipation  FDA: Milk Recalled Over Potential Contamination  How I Learned to Live Fully With Bronchiectasis  The Number-1 Food to Eat for Thyroid Health  A Part of Hearst Digital Media  We may earn commission from links on this page, but we only recommend products we back.  \\u00a92025 Hearst Magazines, Inc. All Rights Reserved.\"}"